  <text>
    <body>
      <div subtype="original" type="letter" xml:id="L.11472" xml:lang="en">
        <pb facs="#IMG.1" n="1"/>
        <dateline>11, NORHAM GARDENS,<lb/>
          <placeName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.9">
OXFORD</placeName>.<lb/> 8 September 1912.<lb/>
        </dateline>
        <opener>Dear Professor Schuchardt,</opener>
        <p>It is very interesting that you are so much occupied with <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.569">Meroitic</ref>. I wish very much that I had spare copies of the books <bibl>
            <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.7292">Karanòg &amp;amp; Meroitic Inscriptions</ref>
          </bibl>,<note n="1" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.7292">
                <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Karanòg, the Meroitic inscriptions of Shablûl and Karanòg</hi>
              </ref>

            </bibl> by F. Ll. Griffith, Philadelphia, Pa., Univ. Museum, 1911.</note> but they are long since gone or promised. The new volume of <hi
            rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">Meroitic Inscriptions</hi> should reach the Academy in a few days. It is entirely devoted to the inscriptions themselves &amp;amp; the same is the case with my Karanòg volume which contains the two series of altars &amp;amp; stelae found by <persName>

MacIver</persName> at Shablûl and Karanôg (Amada and Aniba respectively). The excavations which produced them are described by MacIver and Woolley in other volumes.<note
            n="2" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.8563">
                <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Karanòg, the Romano-Nubian cemetery</hi>
              </ref>

            </bibl>, by C. Leonard Woolley and David Randall-MacIver, Philadelphia, Univ. Museum (Eckley B. Coxe Junior expedition to Nubia), Publications of the Egyptian Department of the University Museum / University of Pennsylvania.</note> It is possible that a copy of Karanôg was sent to Professor <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2494">
Reinisch</persName>.<note n="3" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <persName
              ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2494">Leo Reinisch</persName> (1832-1919), österr. Ägyptologe u. Sprachwissenschaftler, Prof. in <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.3934">Wien</ref>; vgl. HSA 09191-09341; 09341A-09355.</note>
          <pb facs="#IMG.2"
            n="2"/> As to the Faras volume, I am preparing it now, and I shall hope to have the pleasure of sendung you a copy next year.<note
            n="4" place="foot" type="editorial">F. Li. Griffith, <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.8560">
                <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Meroitic Funerary Inscriptions from Faras</hi>
              </ref>
            </bibl>, <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Nubia</hi>, Paris 1922.</note> It will contain an account oft he excavation as well as the inscriptions.</p>
        <p>It is a very serious matter to study so expensive a subject as a mere offshoot of larger studies!</p>
        <p>I have not yet obtained Almkvist’s <bibl>
            <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.8312">Nubian studies</ref>
          </bibl>
          <note n="5" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.8312">
                <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Nubische Studien im Sudān 1877-78</hi>
              </ref>

            </bibl>, aus dem Nachlass Herman Almkvists hrsg. von K. V. Zetterstéen, Uppsala [u. a.], Almqvist &amp;amp; Wiksell [u.a.],1911.</note> which I believe are published by <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.3064">Zettersteen</persName>
          <note n="6" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.3064">Karl Vilhelm Zettersteen</persName> (1866-1953), schwedischer Orientalist; vgl. HSA 13044-13047.</note>, and I do not know where to look for them.</p>

        <p>The Old Nubian texts are practically confined to the <placeName>

Berlin</placeName> MSS and Budgés. I know of no other considerable <pb
            facs="#IMG.3" n="3"/> text but only unintelligible fragments and graffiti.</p>
        <p>[Abb. einscannen]<note n="7" place="foot"
            type="editorial">Hieroglyphen siehe gescanntes Original.</note> = z was a very doubtful equation when I published Karanôg, but in passing the proofs of Inscr. II I found a fairly good proof of it. By <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">z</hi> is meant [einscannen]<note n="8" place="foot" type="editorial">Hieroglyphen siehe gescanntes Original.</note>?</p>
        <p>
          <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">3_</hi> often written I_, especially in the Kalalsha text and then may be confused with (S)¬Z</p>
        <p>It is indeed curious that ḫ and <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">h</hi> exist but not h or ḥ. I use ḫ <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">h</hi> as equivalents of [einscannen Hieroglyphen]<note n="9" place="foot"
            type="editorial">Hieroglyphen siehe gescanntes Original.</note> respectively. Nearly all my sound-identifications come through the rotten unsatisfactory medium of <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.218">Egyptian</ref>.</p>
        <closer>
          <salute>Yours very truly<lb/>
          </salute>
          <signed>
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1643">F. Ll. Griffith.</persName>
          </signed>
        </closer>
      </div>
